title: For Sale:  U.S. Percussion Rifle, Model 1841 - Remington Contract "Mississippi" Musket - Percussion
postcontent:
Model 1841 Remington Contract "Mississippi" Rifle - rifling is faint but is the 7-groove rifling.  Flayderman Guide grades this gun as Fair condition.

M1841 "Mississippis" saw heavy usage by both Confederates and Union soldiers in the early part of the Civil War--usually by state units--but their popularity declined as more 1861 Springfields were manufactured and issued. 

The rear notch sight is intact, and all brass furniture, including barrelbands, triggerguard, sideplate and butt box are intact as is the front sight.  Ramrod is of the Civil-War era full-iron replacement variety, as many of the brass-headed ramrods were removed due to metal separation issues in battle.  Butt-mounted brass patchbox lid hinge is sturdy, patchbox has a compartment for bullet patches, nipple wrench/screwdriver tool, worm and spare percussion nipple.  Brown barrel lacquering (original) is evident in large places along the 33 inch barrel.

Stamped marks on the brass buttstock read "J" over top of a "13".  There are two oval cartouches stamped into the wood on the opposite side from the lock to the rear of the brass curled lockplate on that side.  To the rear of the hammer on the lock is stamped "US 1849", and in front of the hammer, a very faint "Remington's" with some unintelligible stamping below that.

I believe that the very front of of the stock - muzzle end - of the rifle is a piece of replacement wood, although it looks to be a period replacement.  Front brass barrel band is slightly loose due to the lack of humidity in Colorado (rifle is from Pennsylvania).

Asking $900 due to condition and piece of replacement wood (I believe) in stock, or best reasonable offer.  Face-to-face, cash transactions only.  Rifle can be seen at my pub (Scruffy Murphy's Irish Pub, 2030 Larimer Street) by appointment only - please contact me via message through Armslist to arrange.

The Ruger® Redhawk® revolver was Ruger's first double-action revolver specifically designed for the powerful .44 Magnum cartridge. It embodies many advanced features such as a "triple-locking" cylinder, a unique "single spring" mechanism for relatively lighter trigger pull,and adjustable rear sights, with an all-stainless steel construction. Bowen "Rough Country" sights provides a rugged, highly visible replacement sight for current production Ruger revolvers using standard .350" high rear sight. Solid, opposing-tension screws eliminate fragile click movements when making precise adjustments for windage and elevation. Reinforced sight body and a sturdy blade tenon provide extra blade support. Low-profile shape is machined from heat-treated steel alloy, then matte finished to eliminate glare. Revolver has approximately 250 rounds through it, bank vault tight. title: For Trade:  Ruger 10/22 Custom Target Rifle
postcontent: I have a completely custom built from top to bottom stainless 10/22. This is as good as it gets. It has a custom fluted, bull barrel by clerke customs (very expensive, but worth it), and is in a hogue stock. It also has a gunsmith trigger job and the action has been completely polished and honed. Also has a Simmons Master Aetec scope. I do not have to get rid of this rifle, just seeing what else is out there for trade. Just send me a trade offer. Thanks

title: For Sale:  Single shot .50 BMG
postcontent: Single shot Bolt action .50 BMG built on an AR-15 lower.  The upper is from tactilite.  The scope is a Millett LRS 6-24x 56mm.  Magpul PRS stock.  It has about 40 rds through it.  At 20 lbs it is lighter than most rifles chambered in its caliber, and recoil isn't that bad felt recoil is between a 30-06 and a .308.  I will also include most all of the brass i have for it.

title: For Sale:  50 Caliber Glock
postcontent:
The Guncrafter Industries 50GI cartridge was designed from the ground up.  It is a very strong, thick-walled cartridge which when loaded is approximately the same OAL as a standard .45ACP round. Due to the larger caliber, the cartridge operates at relatively low pressure and has a long reloading life.

The concept was to create a practical 50 caliber pistol without unnecessary bulk and weight but with the benefits of increased knockdown power while still being completely controllable during rapid fire. The 50GI was intended primarily as a self-defense round but is still very versatile and can be loaded to higher or lower levels if desired. 

The attributes of the listing say 50 Action Express, but this is the 50 GI, it is a totally different cartridge, see pictures below.  

50 GI with a 300 Grain JHP at 950 fps has more knockdown power than a 44 Magnum 240 gr JHP going 1350 fps.  

Taylor Knockdown ratings:
50 GI 300 Grain JHP @950 fps = 20.36
44 Mag 240 Grain JHP @1350 fps = 19.86

title: For Sale/Trade:  Hakim 8mm Battle Rifle
postcontent:
I have an Hakim 8mm semi-auto battle rifle I might be interested in trading for the right offer. Looking for unique firearms that I couldn't go out and find locally.

Internals/metal are in good shape. Bolt functions like it should, and there has been no cutting or bubba type shenanigans anywhere. This gun is stock.
The wood has some dings in it, but they're minor and could be cleaned up if someone was so inclined. I didn't want to alter this rifle in any way, so I haven't tried.

These were made in the 50's and 60's by Egypt using machines that originally made the Swedish AG-42, which is similar in action but a different caliber.
These rifles were some of the first direct impingement battle rifles. Only 70,000 or so were ever made, and of that only a couple thousand were imported into the US. They have an adjustable gas system, excellent muzzle break, and are fed by 10 round detachable box magazines.

Bore and crown are in good shape, the bore is PRISTINE and it shoots straight as an arrow. Took it out recently and put about 60 rounds of Yugo FMJ through it and it ran flawlessly.
Have a couple boxes of ammo still on clips to go with it.

Any other questions, just ask.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Nickel plated Colt Vest Pocket .25 with custom grips
postcontent:
This was an impulse buy that I just had to have, but after a month I'm thinking that this pistol just isn't a good match for me.

This pistol is in beautiful shape and functions perfectly. The fellow I got it from said it had been in his Aunt's house since she purchased it new in box and was probably never fired. He fired 3 magazines through it with no issues. After I got it I took it to the range and fired another 3 magazines with no issues. So, less than 50 rounds down the pipe.

This pistol was manufactured in 1924. As was common with many of these pistols, the nickel plating was not factory original, nor were the white grips it came with. I still have the original white Franzite grips, but replaced them with a new set of laser etched checkered walnut grips based on the original COLT pony style that look great. I have the original box as well. I am guessing the nickle plating is better than 95% -- only noticeable loss is on the side of the magazine itself, with two pinhead sized spots missing at the extractor and muzzle crown which are easily overlooked. No other scratches or dings of note.

Pistol is worth about 650, but I got a good deal on it and do not expect to get that much out of it in this economy. Grips cost me about 70.

Although I could really use the cash, I'd like to trade this for something else, preferably something of lesser value plus cash. I am interested in .380 ACP right now, but not terribly fond of polymer or striker fired. I prefer aluminum alloy frames or steel. I like the SIG 230/232 and Bersa Thunder. Would especially be interested in a Thunder with satin nickel frame and slide. Will consider other interesting .380 pistols, including double stacks. Would also consider a Beretta Jetfire .25 as a partial trade.  Will entertain fair and reasonable cash offers as well.

I noticed another ad posted for a nickel Colt .25 yesterday, but this is a different pistol and seller.  Will try to get pics up later tonight.
